Persian Gulf Stocks: Agility, Al Khaliji of Qatar, Etisalat

-- B y   A l a a   S h a h i n e
-- 
2011-06-09T12:27:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/persian-gulf-stocks-agility-al-khaliji-of-qatar-etisalat.html
Qatar’s benchmark  QE Index (DSM)  climbed
1.1 percent, the most since May 11, to 8,276.27 at the 1:30 p.m.
close in Doha. Dubai’s measure, Oman’s gauge and  Abu Dhabi ’s
measure each rose 0.3 percent.  The following stocks rose or fell in the Persian Gulf
region. Symbols are in parentheses.  Agility (AGLTY)   gained the most since June 1, climbing
1.5 percent to 350 fils. Shareholders of the Kuwaiti storage and
transport company approved the cancellation of a 25 percent
capital increase.  Al Khaliji (KCBK)   gained 2.1 percent to 16.94 riyals.
The Qatari lender that abandoned a merger with International
Bank of Qatar will seek a  credit rating  this year and may issue
bonds by the first quarter of 2012, acting Chief Executive
Officer Robin McCall said.  Emirates Telecommunications Corp. (ETISALAT UH) rose 0.9
percent to 10.70 dirhams, the highest since March 30. The  Middle
East ’s biggest telephone company said it has no plans to utilize
a bond program it set up in November.  Emirates NBD PJSC (EMIRATES)   gained 2.2 percent to 4.20
dirhams, the highest level since April 27. The United Arab
Emirates’ biggest bank by assets may consider acquisitions to
expand its funds-management business, Reuters reported, citing
the lender’s Asia-Pacific director for asset management.  Qatar Telecom QSC (QTEL QD) rose 2.9 percent, the most
since April 5, to 154.80 riyals. The emirate’s biggest company
by revenue appointed Nasser Marafih as group chief executive
officer. Sheikh Saud Bin Nasser Al Thani will replace Marafih as
the CEO in Qatar. Waleed Al-Sayed was appointed chief operating
officer, succeeding Nick Dent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Alaa Shahine in Dubai at 
 asalha@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Claudia Maedler at 
 cmaedler@bloomberg.net  